rs to this volume call into question the often-presumed monolithic identity of this broad philosophical front. The volume also highlights the richness and complexity of religion in China during this period, examining the relationship between the Way of the Celestial Master and local, popular religious beliefs and practices, and discussing the relationship between religious Daoism and Buddhism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aBuddhismzChinaxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aPhilosophy and religionxChinaxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aPhilosophy and religionzChinaxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aTaoismzChinaxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Studies. 4aHistory : History. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aBerkowitz, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBokenkamp, Stephen R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChan, Alan K. L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChan, Alan K. L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChua, Jude Soo-Meng, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHon, Tze-Ki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKu, Kathy Cheng-Mei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLai, Chi-Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLo, Yuet-Keung, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLo, Yuet-Keung, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMair, Victor H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiddendorf, Ulrike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZiporyn, Brook, econtributo